    A Fantastic Church with A Great View
    A thirty minute taxi drive to right by the church seemed like a sensible way to start the trip, that was until it came time to leave when trying to buy a one way ticket down on the funicular was a nightmare of queueing and miscommunication. Anyway, the church inside is impressive with the usual mix of vaulted ceilings, impressive stained glass and frescos. The real highlight though is up on the roof and the view for miles out across the city and the surrounding forests. A great place to visit if you have exhausted the city centre itself and have young kids that would enjoy the pretty basic amusement park outside the church, if you are sensible and left the kids at home just enjoy the views.

Mike D

Perfect
Nov 2024 • Family
Go. You probably just paid $36 for Sagrada Familia and/or $47 for the Cathedral of Barcelona. This one is free AND you will not find a better view of the city. Period. If you go to Barcelona, you won’t want to miss this.

If you have an all-zone metro card, that gets you all the way there. Get to Catalina Station. Take the S2 to Peu del Funicular (the other one costs money). Your card gets you onto the cable car up the mountain. At the top, exit the building and turn right. You will see a bus stop sign for Bus 111. Your card gets you on that. It takes you directly to the front of the Cathedral. Two levels of the Cathedral are free to entire and the tile work is STUNNINGLY beautiful. If you want to climb to the very top, right to the statue of Jesus, it costs $5 and you have majestic scenic pictures in every direction.

WELL worth the time to get there.
Written November 2, 2024

Normally I would say don’t bother with the Temple Expiatori del Sagrat Cor de Jesús (Temple of the Sacred Heart of Jesus) as internally it’s a pretty average church compared to others in Barcelona. But much of its attraction comes from its privileged location on one of the highest peaks in the city, from which you get truly excellent views. But once you’ve made it up here you might as well take a look at the inside of the church, which oddly is on two levels. The ground level has some impressive frescos and stained glass windows, then the upper level once you climb the steps is more about the columns to the roof space but still has some nice statues and features. However, it’s the views from here that really win the day.

geo3
Calgary, Canada2,167 contributions
Wonderful views of Barcelona
Jun 2023 • Solo
I am definitely coming back here if I am ever in Barcelona; this was a highlight. As other people have said, the church is not really the attraction, but the views of Barcelona are. They are spectacular.

To add to the confusion, there are two funiculars to the general area: one which is expensive (the one that goes directly up to the Tibidabo), and one which is free with a transit day pass but which requires an additional short bus ride to get to the templo area. Since I had a three-day pass for Barcelona transit, I took the free funicular. To get to the funicular, use the S1 subway line to get to the Peu del Funicular subway stop. At this point the bottom station of the funicular is a short walk from the subway station, and you can take the funicular up (go all the way to the Vallvidrera Superior station at the end; there is an intermediate station as well which you ignore). After this, turn right out of the station, walk a short block, turn right again, and you are at the bus stop which will take you up to the Templo area (bus #111 at time of writing). It's about a 15-minute trip, and is also included in the transit pass. It's quite a scenic ride. Buses are frequent, about every 15 minutes.

After enjoying the view and the temple, I decided to walk back to the upper funicular station rather than taking the bus. It's a 2 km walk, almost all downhill, and it takes about 30 minutes. It is really worthwhile if the weather is nice, since there are frequently beautiful views of Barcelona from the sidewalk. You'll walk past part of the Tibidabo amusement park on the way. Just make sure to turn right when coming down from the Templo area when you arrive at the T-intersection about 800 m into the walk back.

And then back down the funicular, and on to the subway - all in all, a great place to visit.
Written April 20, 2024

New York35 contributions
Uber/Taxi instead of Bus Tour
Oct 2023 • Couples
We took an Uber from the city center to the top (approx 25 Euro). We were able to walk around inside the Cathedral and the grounds for about 45 minutes. We walked back to the car/taxi drop off area and was unable to order an uber back down. Not sure if it was due to lack of availability or uber app just isn’t as popular in Spain. We flagged down one of the cabs that dropped folks off to bring us back to the main city (approx 20 Euro). In peak season I’m sure it’s easier to secure an Uber/taxi. If you’re willing to take the risk it’s much easier than the bus tour.

There is no charge to enter the cathedral.
